Provenance: Frederick Smith (
1805–1879
) described this species merely as from Sri Lanka (then Ceylon ). However, the label code of the lectotype indicates that the specimen was purchased by the Natural History Museum in London as part of lot 23 in 1853 . According to the register at the museum, this lot was sold by Hugh Cuming (
1791–1865
), an insect dealer from London, and originated from Sri Lanka where it had been collected by George Henry Kendrick Thwaites (
1811–1882
). Thwaites went to Sri Lanka in 1849 as director or superintendent of the historical and important Royal Botanical Gardens of Peradeniya, near the city of Kandy in the Central Province (Anon 1882 a, 1882 b). Presumably the type specimen must have been collected around this area, although Thwaites also traveled to other parts of Sri Lanka during his time in Sri Lanka .
